export const COMMON_MISTAKES: string = "# Common Mistakes — What Gets YC Applications Rejected\n\nSource: distilled from YC Roaster's production evaluation rubrics (`src/lib/ai-judge.ts`). These are the penalty signals that score poorly across all 7 dimensions.\n\n---\n\n## The master list\n\n### 1. \"We believe X\" without evidence\n\nThis phrase and its variants (\"we think,\" \"we feel,\" \"we expect\") are assertion disguised as insight. They appear constantly in weak applications.\n\nBad: \"We believe the market is ready for this solution.\"\nBad: \"We think customers will prefer our approach.\"\n\nThe fix is always the same: replace the belief with the evidence that produced it. If there's no evidence, that's the real problem.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Top-down TAM without bottom-up math\n\n\"The X market is worth $50B\" is not a market analysis. It's a number from a report. YC wants to know how much of what market you can reach with your specific product, priced at your specific price, sold to your specific buyer.\n\nBad: \"The global supply chain market is $19.3T.\"\nBetter: \"There are 80,000 mid-market manufacturers in the US. 20% have the pain we solve. At $12K ACV, our reachable market is ~$190M.\"\n\n---\n\n### 3. Vanity metrics without usage context\n\nNumbers without denominators and context mislead, and experienced reviewers know it.\n\nBad: \"10,000 users\" (out of how many signups? what do they do? how often?)\nBad: \"1 million impressions\" (from an ad campaign, irrelevant)\nBad: \"2,000 waitlist signups\" (conversion to active users?)\n\nThe denominator and retention curve matter as much as the top-line number.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Revenue projections presented as traction\n\nFuture projections are not evidence of current demand. They are a model, and models are assumptions. Listing projected revenue to a reviewer who is looking for proof of demand reads as: \"we have no real traction.\"\n\nBad: \"We expect to reach $1M ARR by end of year.\"\nBetter: \"We're at $8K MRR with 15% MoM growth. At that rate we'd reach $100K MRR in 18 months.\"\n\n---\n\n### 5. One-off anecdotes substituted for patterns\n\nA single Fortune 500 company \"expressing interest\" is not a signal. Neither is one customer who loves the product. YC is looking for repeatable, pattern-forming behavior across multiple independent buyers or users.\n\nBad: \"A VP at Google told us this is exactly what they need.\"\nBetter: \"We have 6 active design partners, 2 of whom have already agreed to convert to paid at $2K/month when we GA.\"\n\n---\n\n### 6. \"We have no competitors\"\n\nThis is almost never true, and it signals poor market research. Every product competes with something — at minimum, it competes with doing nothing or using a spreadsheet. Saying \"no competitors\" makes a reviewer wonder what else you're missing about the market.\n\nThe fix: name the real competitors (including indirect substitutes), then explain your specific insight advantage.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Founders with credentials but no proof of building\n\nA team of MBAs and consultants with impressive resumes who have never shipped a product is a risk pattern. YC bets on builders. Credentials establish context; they don't establish execution capability.\n\nBad: \"Our team has 40+ years of combined experience in [industry].\"\nBetter: \"Our CTO built [Product X], which reached [Y] users before we pivoted to this. Our CEO spent 5 years as a [role] at [company], which is how we know this problem exists.\"\n\n---\n\n### 8. Part-time founders with no commitment plan\n\nFounders who haven't left their jobs to build this product are a signal of low conviction or high opportunity cost. YC moves fast and expects founders to be all-in.\n\nBad: \"We've been working on this nights and weekends for 2 years.\"\nBetter: \"We both went full-time 3 months ago. [Founder] left [job], [co-founder] left [job]. We have 18 months of runway.\"\n\n---\n\n### 9. GTM plan = \"we will do ads / go viral / hire sales later\"\n\nThis pattern appears in almost every weak application. It is not a go-to-market strategy.\n\nBad: \"We plan to acquire users through paid ads, SEO, and social media.\"\nBad: \"Our product will grow through word of mouth.\"\nBad: \"Once we raise our Series A, we'll hire a sales team.\"\n\nBetter: \"Our first 20 customers came from [specific channel]. The conversion from [top of funnel] to paid is [X]%. We've identified [specific next channel] as repeatable because [specific reason].\"\n\n---\n\n### 10. Services disguised as software\n\nA product that requires significant founder or employee time to deliver its value is a service business, not a software business — even if there's a dashboard involved. YC invests in software businesses.\n\nWarning signs:\n- \"We handle the [core task] for customers manually while we build automation\"\n- No clear automation roadmap\n- Gross margin under 40% at current scale\n- Every new customer requires a custom implementation\n\n---\n\n### 11. Moat claims without mechanism\n\n\"Our moat is our data\" or \"our competitive advantage is our proprietary AI\" requires explanation of the mechanism. How does more data make the product better in a way competitors can't replicate? What specifically is proprietary about the AI?\n\nBad: \"Our data moat means competitors can't catch up.\"\nBetter: \"Every customer's data trains a personalized model for that customer. Competitors starting today would need 2+ years of customer data to match our recommendation accuracy on new accounts.\"\n\n---\n\n### 12. Founder-market fit asserted without demonstration\n\n\"We are uniquely positioned to solve this problem\" is a claim, not evidence. The evidence is the story of how you came to know this problem better than anyone else.\n\nBad: \"We have deep domain expertise in logistics.\"\nBetter: \"I spent 4 years as a dispatcher at a regional trucking company. I built the manual process that this software replaces. I know every edge case.\"\n\n---\n\n### 13. \"We plan to\" when the question asks what you've done\n\nA large number of YC application answers substitute future plans for present reality. This is especially common in the progress and traction sections. The question \"how far along are you?\" is asking about the present, not the roadmap.\n\nBad: \"We plan to launch in Q3 and onboard our first paying customers by Q4.\"\nBetter: \"We launched in March. We have 3 paying customers at $500/month. We shipped [feature] last week.\"\n\n---\n\n### 14. The long answer that doesn't answer the question\n\nWord count is not a substitute for substance. An answer that runs 500 words but never directly addresses what YC asked scores worse than a 100-word answer that is precise and specific. Reviewers flag long non-answers as a sign of fuzzy thinking.\n\nThe test: underline the sentence in your answer that directly answers the question. If you can't find one, rewrite.\n";

export const SUCCESSFUL_PATTERNS: string = "# Successful Patterns — What Strong YC Applications Look Like\n\nSource: distilled from YC Roaster's production evaluation rubrics (`src/lib/ai-judge.ts`). These are the signals that score well across all 7 dimensions.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-cutting principles\n\nThe single strongest pattern in successful applications is **evidence over assertion**. Every claim is backed by a number, a named customer, a specific behavior, or a verifiable fact. The weakest applications make claims of equal or greater confidence with none of these.\n\n**Specific beats vague, always.** \"We have 10 paying customers at $500/month with 90% retention\" beats \"we're seeing strong traction.\" \"We talked to 40 potential customers over 6 weeks; 8 asked us to build it and 3 agreed to be design partners\" beats \"we've validated demand.\"\n\n---\n\n## Dimension-by-dimension patterns\n\n### Application Completeness\n\n- Clear explanation of what you're building and who it's for, in plain English, in the first two sentences\n- The 50-character description and the full product description are consistent and reinforce each other\n- Concrete progress: what exists today, what's been shipped, what's next with timelines\n- Clear founder details: who does what, how long they've been working on this, full-time commitment\n- Equity and legal structure addressed without ambiguity\n- Minimal \"Not provided\" or blank answers — every unanswered question is a missed signal\n\n### Early Traction\n\n**For post-launch companies:**\n- Durable usage metrics with denominators: \"47% of users who activated in week 1 returned in week 4\"\n- Month-over-month growth rates: \"22% MoM revenue growth for the last 4 months\"\n- Revenue quality: recurring subscriptions, expanding accounts, low churn\n- Specific paying customers: \"3 enterprise customers at $2K/month, signed in the last 6 weeks\"\n- Organic pull signals: word-of-mouth, inbound that converts, referrals\n\n**For pre-launch companies:**\n- Named user discovery: \"talked to 40 potential customers at [specific companies], learned X\"\n- Credible demand commitments: signed LOIs, deposits, design partner agreements\n- Prototype testing with behavioral signals: \"8 out of 10 users completed the core task in under 2 minutes\"\n- Velocity signals: how fast they're building and iterating\n\n### Team Quality\n\n- Proof of shipping: specific past products with user or revenue numbers (\"built X which got to 5K users / $30K ARR before we shut it down\")\n- Founder-market fit demonstrated, not asserted: \"I spent 3 years as a [role] at [company] dealing with this exact problem\"\n- Technical coverage: someone on the team can build what they're describing without hiring\n- Complementary skills: the business/domain person and the builder are clearly differentiated\n- Full-time commitment: founders who quit their jobs to build this signal conviction\n- Working history together: co-founders who have built things together before are lower risk\n\n### Market\n\n- Clear buyer with acute pain: not \"enterprises\" but \"mid-market logistics companies with 50–200 drivers who are losing $X/month to route inefficiency\"\n- Believable wedge and expansion path: starting narrow, growing logically\n- Why-now argument grounded in a real change: regulation, technology shift, behavior change, infrastructure availability\n- Willingness-to-pay evidence beyond surveys: people who have paid or committed to pay\n- Niche that is a wedge into something large — small + defensible beats large + crowded\n\n### Go-To-Market\n\n- Named ICP with specifics: job title, company size, budget ownership, buying trigger\n- Distribution wedge that's non-obvious: \"we get in through [specific channel/community/integration] that competitors can't use\"\n- Working motion with metrics: \"outbound to [persona] via [channel], 15% reply rate, 30% close rate on qualified calls\"\n- Pricing aligned to the motion: self-serve pricing makes sense at low ACV; sales motion makes sense at high ACV\n- Evidence of learning: \"we tried X, it didn't work, now we're doing Y because Z\"\n\n### Scalability\n\n- Low marginal cost as a structural property, not an aspiration\n- If starting manual: a credible, specific automation roadmap tied to what they're learning manually\n- Structural advantages described mechanically: \"the more data we collect, the better our model gets, which means our accuracy improves and competitors can't catch up without the data\"\n- Architecture that was designed to scale, described with specifics\n- Not a consultancy: the value delivered doesn't scale linearly with founder time\n\n### Monetization\n\n- Simple, credible pricing tied to value: \"we charge $X per [unit] because [buyer] budgets in those units\"\n- Proof of willingness to pay: revenue, LOIs with dollar amounts, discovery conversations where price wasn't an objection\n- Unit economics direction even if early: cost to serve, gross margin, payback period\n- Clear purchase motion: who signs off, how long the cycle takes, what triggers a purchase\n- Bottom-up TAM: \"there are 50K [ICPs] in the US, we can reach 10% of them, at $5K ACV that's a $25M opportunity in the initial market\"\n\n---\n\n## Voice and tone patterns that score well\n\n- Active voice: \"we built X\" not \"X was built\"\n- Past tense for what's done, present tense for what's running, future tense sparingly and tied to specifics\n- Numbers with context: not \"10X growth\" but \"10X growth from $2K to $20K MRR over 4 months\"\n- Named customers without necessarily naming them publicly: \"a top-5 US bank\" or \"a $2B logistics company\" is fine\n- Confidence without hedging: state what you know, acknowledge what you don't know rather than softening everything\n";

export const QUESTION_GUIDANCE: Record<string, string> = {
  "company_description": "# Company Description — \"Describe what your company does in 50 characters or less\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nThis is the hardest question in the application and the first thing a YC partner reads. The 50-character constraint is deliberate: it forces brutal clarity about the core value proposition. If you can't say what you do in 50 characters, you either don't have a clear enough product or you don't understand your own business well enough yet. A strong one-liner instantly communicates the subject (who it's for), the verb (what you do), and the object (what outcome). Adjectives are banned by the constraint.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A subject, a verb, and an object: \"[Product] [does X] for [buyer]\"\n- The specific customer or user — not \"enterprises\" or \"users\" but the actual person\n- The actual action the product takes — not \"transforms\" or \"powers\" but what it literally does\n- No adjectives: no \"AI-powered\", no \"next-generation\", no \"seamless\"\n- Under 50 characters — if it's over, it's wrong on the form\n- Passes the test: a smart person who knows nothing about your space understands it in one read\n\nStrong examples (anonymized patterns):\n- \"Bookkeeping software for Shopify sellers\" (41 chars)\n- \"API to add video calls to any app\" (33 chars)\n- \"Automates SOC2 compliance audits\" (32 chars)\n- \"Background checks in 24 hours\" (29 chars)\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"AI-powered platform for enterprise digital transformation\" — adjectives, no specificity, over 50 chars\n- \"We build the operating system for X\" — the word \"build\" is the founder talking, not the product\n- \"Revolutionizing logistics through data\" — what does that mean?\n- \"The Stripe for healthcare\" — analogy without content; fine as a supplement, not as the description\n- Anything starting with \"We\" — the description is about the product, not the founders\n- Anything that could describe 10 different companies\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"Read that out loud to someone who doesn't know your space. Does it say what you DO or what you ARE?\"\n2. \"Remove every adjective from your description. What's left? Is it still accurate?\"\n3. \"Who is the specific person or company this serves? Is that clear from the 50 characters?\"\n4. \"Is the verb in your description what the product literally does — or is it what you aspire to enable?\"\n5. \"Count the characters. Is it actually under 50?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- README first line or project tagline — often the most honest early version of the one-liner\n- Any existing marketing copy (landing page headline, product hunt tagline)\n- How users describe the product when they refer others (\"I use [X], it's a [description]\")\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note\n\nThe 50-character one-liner and the full product description (next question) must be consistent and reinforce each other. If the one-liner says \"bookkeeping for Shopify sellers\" but the product description describes a general finance platform, there's a contradiction that suggests unclear positioning. Fix both.\n",
  "competitors": "# Competitors — \"Who are your competitors? What do you understand about your business that they don't?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nYC is checking two things: first, that you have honest awareness of the competitive landscape (no \"there are no competitors\" answers); second, that you have a genuine insight — something you understand about the problem, the buyer, or the market that your competitors have missed or ignored. The insight is the important part. A list of competitors without an insight reads as market research, not strategy.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- Named competitors, including indirect substitutes (what customers use today, even if it's a spreadsheet or a manual process)\n- A specific insight stated in one or two sentences: \"They serve [buyer A] because [reason]. We've found that [buyer B] has the same pain with higher urgency and no solution — and [buyer A] players can't easily serve them because [structural reason].\"\n- An explanation of why the insight is durable — why incumbents can't just copy the approach\n- The wedge customer segment: who competitors are ignoring that you're targeting first\n- Evidence that the insight came from research or experience, not just reasoning\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"There are no direct competitors\" — almost never true, and signals poor research\n- Lists Salesforce, Microsoft, or Google without explaining why the applicant can compete with them\n- \"We're different because we use AI\" — every company says this; it's not an insight\n- \"Our competitive advantage is our team\" — team is not a market insight\n- \"We will outcompete because we're faster and more agile\" — a plan, not an insight\n- Naming competitors correctly but failing to state any specific insight about what they're missing\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"What do potential customers use today to solve this problem? Even if it's a spreadsheet or a manual process, name it.\"\n2. \"Have you signed up for and used the top 3 competitors? What did you find that you can't find anywhere publicly?\"\n3. \"What do competitors get wrong that you get right? Give me one sentence.\"\n4. \"Why can't the largest player in this space just add a feature that competes with you?\"\n5. \"Which competitor do you respect most and why? What would it take to beat them specifically?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- Competitive analysis notes or documents\n- Screenshots or accounts in competitor products (shows they've actually used them)\n- Customer feedback that explicitly mentions switching from a competitor or comparing to one\n- Any recorded user interviews where the competitor landscape came up\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note on the insight question\n\nThe insight question is where most founders leave the most points on the table. They name competitors correctly but then answer \"what do you understand that they don't\" with a feature list (\"we have better UX, faster onboarding, lower price\"). That's not an insight — that's a positioning statement. The real answer is structural: \"They built for [buyer X] because that's the easiest to reach, but [buyer Y] has 3x the pain, spends 3x as much on the problem, and is systematically underserved because [specific reason competitors can't serve them].\" Push founders to get to that level.\n",
  "curious": "# Curious — \"What convinced you to apply to Y Combinator?\"\n\nAlso covers: \"How did you hear about Y Combinator?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nThis is the lowest-stakes section of the application. YC is not making major decisions based on this answer — they're checking for basic authenticity and self-awareness. They want to see that you understand what YC actually provides beyond the check, and that you have a genuine reason for wanting to be in the program. Generic answers (\"YC is the best accelerator\") don't hurt you, but a specific, honest answer can add a small positive signal.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A specific reason for YC beyond the money: the network, the alumni community, the batch experience, the specific partners, the \"do things that don't scale\" ethos\n- Optional: a specific YC company or alumni story that influenced the decision\n- \"How did you hear\" answered honestly — it's genuinely just a logistics question for YC's own tracking\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"YC is the best accelerator in the world\" — generic, adds nothing\n- \"We need the funding\" — honest but signals you're optimizing for the check rather than the program\n- \"A friend told me to apply\" with no elaboration on why YC specifically\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"What specifically about how YC operates do you think would help you most at this stage?\"\n2. \"Is there a specific YC company, founder, or essay that shaped how you think about building?\"\n3. \"What would you do differently in the next 6 months if you get into YC vs. if you don't?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\nNone needed. This is about motivation and genuine interest, not external evidence.\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note\n\nDon't over-engineer this answer. A genuine two to three sentences outperforms a long essay every time. The answer should sound like something a real person would say, not a carefully optimized marketing message. If the founder has a genuine connection to a specific YC founder or company, that's worth mentioning — it shows they've thought about this beyond the prestige signal.\n",
  "equity": "# Equity — Legal entity, investment, and fundraising\n\nCovers three questions:\n- \"Have you formed ANY legal entity yet?\"\n- \"Have you taken any investment yet?\"\n- \"Are you currently fundraising?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nYC is checking for cap table issues that would complicate their investment, and for basic company hygiene. They invest via a standard SAFE at a fixed valuation cap — anything that makes that harder (messy cap table, conflicting investor terms, no incorporation) creates friction. This section is mostly a hygiene check, not a differentiation opportunity. The goal is a clean, direct answer with no surprises.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- **Legal entity**: clear yes/no, with entity type and state of incorporation (\"Delaware C-Corp, incorporated March 2024\")\n- **Equity split**: clear founder equity percentages, with vesting schedule noted (\"70/30 split, 4-year vesting with 1-year cliff, started vesting January 2024\")\n- **Investment**: if taken, name the amount, type (SAFE, priced round, convertible note), and the valuation cap or discount\n- **Fundraising**: direct yes/no; if yes, state the round size, target, and current status\n- **No surprises**: if there are complicated terms or non-standard structures, disclose and explain them briefly\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"We plan to incorporate\" — not incorporated means YC would need to wait, which reduces their interest\n- Complicated cap table with many small angel investors and no lead\n- \"We have a verbal agreement with an investor\" — verbal is not real; only signed documents count\n- Unclear equity split between founders, especially without vesting (\"we split it 50/50\")\n- \"We haven't discussed equity yet\" — founders who haven't aligned on this create risk; fix this before applying\n- Significant outside investment at a valuation that might make YC's standard terms difficult\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"Are you incorporated? What entity type, what state, what date?\"\n2. \"What's the cap table right now? Who owns what percentage, with vesting?\"\n3. \"Have you taken any money? From whom, what amount, what type of instrument, and what were the terms?\"\n4. \"Is there anything in your current cap table or prior agreements that a YC investment might conflict with?\"\n5. \"If you're fundraising: what's the round size, how much is committed, and what's your timeline?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- Incorporation documents (entity type, state, date — not the full docs, just the facts)\n- Cap table summary: founder names, percentages, vesting schedules, any other shareholders\n- Any SAFEs, convertible notes, or equity agreements with key terms (cap, discount, MFN)\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note on vesting\n\nFounders with no vesting schedule on their equity are a red flag to sophisticated investors including YC. It means if one founder leaves early, they walk away with a large chunk of the company. If founders haven't set up vesting yet, they should do it before submitting — and then answer this question accurately.\n",
  "idea_origin": "# Idea Origin — \"Why did you pick this idea to work on?\"\n\nFull question: \"Do you have domain expertise in this area? How do you know people need what you're making?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nThis is the founder-market fit question. YC is asking: why are you specifically the right person to build this? The answer needs to show one of three things — lived experience with the problem, deep domain expertise from a relevant career, or unusually close proximity to the customer (talked to many, worked with them, are one of them). A team that \"saw a market opportunity\" is much weaker than a team that has been frustrated by this problem for years and finally decided to fix it themselves.\n\nThe second half — \"how do you know people need this\" — is the demand validation question. YC wants evidence, not conviction.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A specific origin story: \"I spent 3 years doing X and was frustrated by Y every single time\"\n- Domain expertise grounded in work history: \"I was a [role] at [company] and dealt with this problem directly for [N] years\"\n- Specific demand validation: \"I talked to 30 potential customers; 8 said they'd switch to this immediately and 3 are already design partners\"\n- Insider knowledge of the problem space that someone reading about it for a week wouldn't have\n- A clear reason why this team has an advantage that others don't: access, expertise, relationships, insight\n- Willingness to name specific people who told them they need this\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"We saw a market opportunity in X\" — no personal connection, no insider knowledge\n- \"The market is large and growing\" — market analysis, not demand proof\n- \"We ran a survey and 80% said they'd use this\" — surveys are not demand proof; people lie on surveys\n- \"We talked to potential customers\" without naming how many, what they said, or whether they committed to anything\n- Founder-market fit asserted without backstory: \"We have deep expertise in logistics\" with no evidence\n- \"Users told us they want this\" without specifics or names\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"When did you first encounter this problem personally? Walk me through what happened.\"\n2. \"What do you know about this space that someone reading about it for a week wouldn't know?\"\n3. \"Name two potential customers you've talked to. What did they tell you, exactly? Did any of them ask you to build this before you started?\"\n4. \"Why you specifically? What's the unfair advantage you have over 5 other teams who could theoretically build this?\"\n5. \"What's the one insight about this problem that your competitors are missing?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- Customer discovery notes or interview transcripts — even rough bullet points from calls\n- Any written communications from potential customers asking for the product\n- Past work history relevant to the problem (LinkedIn is context; shipped work is evidence)\n- Competitive research they've done that reveals the insight competitors are missing\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note on the demand validation trap\n\n\"We know people need this because we talked to them\" is much stronger than \"we know people need this because the market is large.\" But even talking to people has a floor: a handful of conversations with friends or former colleagues is less credible than 30+ structured conversations with target buyers who have no relationship obligation to be nice. Push for numbers, push for whether any of them committed to anything.\n",
  "location": "# Location — \"Where do you live now, and where would the company be based after YC?\"\n\nAlso covers: \"Explain your decision regarding location.\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nYC's batch is in person in San Francisco. The location question is primarily checking: will you actually be in SF? If you're outside the US, it's also checking for visa awareness. The \"explain your decision\" follow-up is looking for strategic thinking about why your current location makes sense for the business — not a defense of remote work as a philosophy.\n\nThis is not a trick question. Answer it directly.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A direct answer to where founders live now and where the company will be based post-YC\n- \"We'll be in San Francisco for the full batch\" — if true, say it clearly\n- If currently outside SF: a specific, realistic relocation plan (\"We're in Berlin, will move to SF for the batch, planning to stay 6–12 months to build customer relationships\")\n- If outside the US: acknowledgment of visa requirements and awareness of the timeline\n- If staying in a different city: a compelling strategic reason that benefits the business (major customer base, specific talent market, regulatory advantage)\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"We'll figure out the logistics\" — no plan\n- A long essay about why remote work is the future — doesn't answer the question YC actually asked\n- Ignoring the relocation question entirely\n- Visa uncertainty with no evidence of having looked into it\n- \"We plan to be in SF\" with no acknowledgment of what that requires if they're currently elsewhere\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"Will you be in San Francisco in person for the full YC batch — yes or no?\"\n2. \"If you're not already in SF, what's your specific relocation plan? Have you looked at housing?\"\n3. \"If you're outside the US, have you researched the visa requirements for the batch?\"\n4. \"Is there a strategic reason you're currently in [location] that YC should know?\"\n5. \"What's your plan for the company's base after the batch — stay in SF or return?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- Generally none needed — this is a logistics and planning question\n- If the founder claims their current location is strategic (customer proximity, talent market), ask them to name specific customers or hires that validate that claim\n",
  "monetization": "# Monetization — \"How do or will you make money? How much could you make?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nYC is not expecting certainty on monetization — they fund many pre-revenue companies. What they are checking is whether the founders have thought clearly about value capture: who pays, why they pay, what they pay, and whether the model can reach a meaningful scale. The \"how much could you make\" part is asking for a bottom-up estimate, not a projection from a top-down market size.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A named pricing model with a rationale: \"SaaS at $200/month per seat because our buyers budget in seat-based tools and that's what they compare us to\"\n- Evidence of willingness to pay: paying customers, LOIs with dollar amounts, discovery calls where price wasn't an objection\n- Unit economics direction even if rough: \"cost to serve a customer is about $20/month, we price at $200 — leaves room for CAC and growth\"\n- Clear buyer and purchase motion: who approves the purchase, who pays, what triggers a buying decision\n- Bottom-up TAM reasoning: \"there are 80K mid-market manufacturers in the US, we can reach 10% in 3 years, at $12K ACV that's ~$100M\"\n- For pre-revenue: a credible pricing hypothesis and why it's grounded in buyer behavior\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"We will monetize through advertising eventually\" — almost never works for B2B; requires massive scale for B2C\n- \"We'll charge $X per [unit] once we have users\" — no evidence of WTP\n- Revenue projections without underlying assumptions: \"we'll reach $10M ARR in 3 years\"\n- Pricing copied directly from competitors without evidence it works for the specific segment\n- \"We'll figure out monetization after we have scale\" — acceptable for some consumer plays but must be justified\n- Commission-based models with no current transaction volume to anchor the estimate\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"Have you charged anyone yet? What happened when you first asked for money?\"\n2. \"What's your current pricing? Why that number — not half of it, not double?\"\n3. \"Who approves the purchase decision at your target customer? What does that process look like?\"\n4. \"What's your gross margin at current pricing? What does it converge to at scale?\"\n5. \"Build me a bottom-up market estimate: how many buyers, at what price, reachable by when?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- Revenue records or payment history (even one payment is meaningful)\n- Any pricing page, pricing experiments, or pricing conversation notes\n- Customer discovery notes where willingness to pay came up\n- Comparable pricing data from the competitive landscape they've researched\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note on the TAM question\n\nThe \"how much could you make\" question is an invitation to show bottom-up thinking. Top-down TAM answers (\"the market is $19B\") tell a reviewer nothing about whether this specific product at this specific price can reach a meaningful number. The bottom-up version (\"there are 80K of my target buyers, I can reach 10% at my current ACV in 3 years\") is what YC actually wants. Push founders to build this from the specific buyer up, not from the market report down.\n",
  "product_description": "# Product Description — \"What is your company going to make?\"\n\nFull question: \"Please describe your product and what it does or will do.\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nYC wants to know the specific thing you're building. Not the market. Not the problem. The product — what it is, what a user does with it on day one, and what exists right now vs. what's planned. The most common failure here is describing the problem in detail and then vaguely gesturing at a solution (\"we're building a platform that addresses this\"). Reviewers notice when founders write more about the pain than the product, and they flag it as a sign the product isn't real yet.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A description of what a user literally does in the product — the core workflow\n- What exists today that someone could use right now (present tense, specific)\n- What's being built next (roadmap, tied to the current progress, not a wishlist)\n- The form factor: is it a web app, API, mobile app, physical device, script?\n- Who the user is — specific enough that you could name them\n- How the product delivers value: what changes for the user after they use it?\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- More paragraphs about the problem than about the product\n- \"We are building a platform that allows companies to X\" — \"platform\" is a vague noun; \"allows\" is doing no work\n- \"Our AI-powered solution enables seamless X\" — every adjective here is meaningless\n- All roadmap, no present: \"We will build X, then Y, then Z\" with no mention of what exists now\n- The answer contradicts the 50-char description — different products described in each\n- The product described requires technology that doesn't exist yet without acknowledging that\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"What does a user actually do on day one of using this? Walk me through the exact steps.\"\n2. \"What exists today that I could open right now and use? Show me or describe it specifically.\"\n3. \"What is the single most important feature — the one thing that makes this useful at all?\"\n4. \"If you ran a 60-second demo, what would you show? In what order?\"\n5. \"Is the product described here consistent with what you described in your 50-char answer?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- README — product overview section; often has the clearest description of what was actually built\n- Recent commit history — what features have been shipped in the last 60 days\n- Any demo recording or link\n- User-facing docs or onboarding flow — shows what users see and do\n- For code-heavy products: architecture diagram or top-level module descriptions\n",
  "progress": "# Progress — \"How far along are you?\"\n\nAlso covers: time commitment, tech stack, previous batches, incubator participation.\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nThis section is where YC calibrates velocity and commitment. They want to see that you're building fast, that everyone is serious about the company, and that you have a working product — not just a plan. The tech stack question is a reality check: vague or aspirational answers suggest the product isn't built yet. The \"same idea as previous batch\" question catches applicants who are reapplying without having changed anything meaningful.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- Specific milestones with dates: \"We launched a closed beta in February with 20 users; we opened public access in April\"\n- A working product that someone can use or has used\n- Full-time commitment with a specific date: \"both co-founders went full-time on March 1st\"\n- Named tech stack with real choices: \"Next.js, Postgres on Supabase, deployed on Railway; Python FastAPI for the ML backend\"\n- Velocity signal: what changed in the last 30–60 days, not just current state\n- If reapplying: a specific, substantive description of what changed (\"last time we were pre-revenue; we now have 3 paying customers and have pivoted the ICP from SMBs to mid-market\")\n- If in another program: direct disclosure with the relevant terms\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"We're still building the MVP\" — no signal of what's been done\n- \"We've been working on this for 2 years part-time\" — slow velocity, low commitment\n- Tech stack described as \"modern AI frameworks\" or \"cloud-based architecture\" — aspirational, not real\n- Progress described entirely as future plans (\"we plan to ship X in Q3\")\n- \"Our prototype is almost ready\" — \"almost\" is doing a lot of work\n- Timeline jumps from \"we had the idea\" to \"we built a product\" with nothing in between\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"What existed in this product 90 days ago vs. what exists today — specifically?\"\n2. \"Is everyone on the team full-time? If not, what is the trigger for going full-time?\"\n3. \"Tell me your tech stack: language, framework, database, hosting — name them all.\"\n4. \"What did you ship last week? Not plan — ship.\"\n5. \"If this is a reapplication: what specifically changed since last time, and how do you know it was the right change?\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- **Git log**: `git log --oneline --since=\"90 days ago\" --format=\"%ad %s\" --date=short` — shows real commit velocity\n- **package.json, requirements.txt, Cargo.toml, or equivalent** — names the actual tech stack\n- **README or changelog** — describes what's been built\n- **Any deployment config** (Dockerfile, vercel.json, fly.toml) — confirms the product is actually deployed somewhere\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note on the \"almost ready\" trap\n\n\"Almost ready\" is a red flag phrase. If the MVP is almost ready, it's not ready — and YC knows the difference. Push the founder to describe what is actually working and usable today, even if limited. A working 10% of the product is more credible than a 90% complete product that nobody can use yet.\n",
  "team": "# Team — \"Who writes code, or does other technical work on your product?\"\n\nAlso covers: \"Was any of it done by a non-founder?\" and \"Are you looking for a cofounder?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nYC is checking whether the founding team can build the product. A team where no founder writes code is a structural red flag — it means technical decisions depend on people who don't have equity and can walk away. Beyond technical coverage, YC is evaluating founder-market fit (does the team have an unfair advantage from lived experience?), commitment (are they all-in?), and complementarity (do the founders cover the key dimensions of the business without gaps?).\n\nSolo founders are not disqualifying, but they carry extra scrutiny: YC wants to see execution velocity that compensates for the single point of failure.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n- A named person who writes production code, with a description of what they've specifically built in this product\n- Evidence of prior shipping: a past product, system, or company with user or revenue numbers attached\n- Clear role division: who builds, who sells, who knows the domain\n- Full-time commitment from everyone, or a specific and near-term plan to get there\n- Co-founder working history: built something together before, know each other well\n- For solo founders: a track record of rapid, independent execution that compensates for the team risk\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"We're looking for a CTO\" — no technical capability on the team right now\n- \"Our technical co-founder has 15 years of experience\" — credentials without evidence of shipping\n- \"We use contractors to build the product\" — technical work is entirely outside the equity structure\n- \"We all contribute to the product\" — roles are unclear, no one is clearly accountable for building\n- \"We've been working on this nights and weekends\" — part-time with no commitment plan\n- \"I handle the business side and my co-founder handles the technical side\" — fine, but needs proof of what \"technical side\" means in practice\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"Who in the founding team wrote the last 10 commits? What did they do?\"\n2. \"What's the last thing [technical co-founder] shipped before this company? Did it work?\"\n3. \"Is everyone on the team full-time? If not, when does that change, and what's the trigger?\"\n4. \"Have you worked together before? What did you build, and how did it go?\"\n5. \"If you're a solo founder: what did you build last month? Walk me through it.\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- **Git log**: `git log --oneline --format='%an %s' | head -30` — shows who is actually committing and what\n- **GitHub contributor graph** — if accessible, shows velocity and distribution of work\n- **README or codebase structure** — to verify the technical founder actually understands what's been built\n- **Past product links or demos** — from before this company, to prove shipping history\n- **LinkedIn** is acceptable context for background but push for shipped-product evidence, not credentials\n\n---\n\n## Coaching note on cofounder search\n\nIf the founder is actively looking for a co-founder, they should be direct about it and explain what gap they're filling. Hiding this looks worse than admitting it. The answer \"yes, we're looking for a technical co-founder — here's why we can still make progress without one\" is more credible than pretending the team is complete.\n",
  "traction": "# Traction — \"Are people using your product?\" + \"Do you have revenue?\"\n\n---\n\n## What YC is actually evaluating\n\nTraction is the single highest-signal section for most applications. It is the closest thing to proof that the idea works, that the market wants it, and that this team can execute. YC calibrates very carefully here: they've seen thousands of applications with inflated traction claims and they know exactly what real traction looks like vs. vanity metrics.\n\nThe goal of this section is to show **pull from the world** — that customers are coming to you, using the product repeatedly, and paying or willing to pay.\n\n---\n\n## What strong answers contain\n\n**For post-launch companies:**\n- Specific numbers with denominators: \"47 paying customers, $8K MRR, 15% MoM growth over 4 months\"\n- Retention signal: \"80% of users who activated in month 1 returned in month 3\"\n- Revenue quality: recurring subscriptions, low churn, expanding accounts\n- Specific paying customer descriptions: company size, use case, how they found you\n- Growth curve, not just current state: show the direction and rate of change\n- Organic pull: how users are finding you (word of mouth, inbound, referrals)\n\n**For pre-launch companies:**\n- Named user discovery: \"talked to 40 potential customers at [specific types of companies], here's what we learned\"\n- Credible demand commitments: signed LOIs, deposits, design partner agreements (named if possible)\n- Waitlist with conversion signal — not just how many people signed up but what percentage activated\n- Prototype testing with behavioral data: \"8 out of 10 target users completed the core task; avg session was 12 minutes\"\n- Speed and velocity: how fast you're moving, how quickly you're learning\n\n---\n\n## What weak answers look like\n\n- \"10,000 users\" with no retention, activation, or engagement context\n- Waitlist numbers only: \"5,000 people signed up\" — what percentage converted to active users?\n- \"Our beta users love it\" — sentiment without data\n- Paid acquisition with no retention: \"we spent $500 on ads and got 200 signups\" — what happened after?\n- A Fortune 500 company \"expressed interest\" — one anecdote is not a pattern\n- Revenue projections: \"we expect $1M ARR by year end\" — this is a model, not traction\n- Testimonials without usage data\n\n---\n\n## Probing questions to ask the founder\n\n1. \"What's your retention rate at 30 days? At 90 days?\"\n2. \"How many of your users are paying? What do they pay? How long have they been paying?\"\n3. \"Where did your users come from — organic, paid, referral? What's the conversion rate from each?\"\n4. \"Name one customer who would do a reference call with a YC partner right now. What would they say?\"\n5. \"If pre-launch: who specifically have you talked to? What did they say? Did any of them ask you to build this before you built it?\"\n6. \"What's your MoM growth rate over the last 3 months? Not projected — actual.\"\n\n---\n\n## Evidence to request from the founder's local files\n\n- **Analytics export** (CSV or JSON): DAU, WAU, MAU, retention cohorts — even a screenshot of a dashboard with real data\n- **Revenue records**: MRR, ARR, churn data, payment history from Stripe or equivalent\n- **Customer list** (can be anonymized): number of customers, when they signed, what they pay\n- **LOIs or signed contracts**: even draft versions show credibility\n- **Customer interview notes**: what users said in their own words — the specific quotes, not the paraphrase\n- Any **NPS or CSAT data** if available\n"
};
